There appears to be confusion among informal traders about who is allowed to operate. #Day11ofLockdown #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - There appears to be confusion among informal traders about who is allowed to operate during the lockdown. Last week, the National Command Council said informal food traders will be allowed to do business. But according to regulations, only those selling raw produce are included. Informal traders selling fast-food are not cleared to trade. SA Lockdown: Informal food traders allowed to operate The City of Cape Town will from Tuesday begin a new application process for informal traders. Many informal traders in townships have been forced by law enforcement to close their businesses. The City of Cape Town is imposing fines of up to R5,000 for those who don't obey. READ: Coronavirus in SA: Limpopo traders concerned It says those wanting a permit to trade will have to provide their existing permits. Government's decision to prohibit informal traders from selling fast-food is to maintain social distancing. The only way for traders to operate now will be to have a delivery service – which many can't afford. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.